=========================================
C++14 DIGIT SEPARATORS (')
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What are Digit Separators?

Digit Separators were introduced in C++14.

They allow single quotes (') to be inserted inside numeric literals to improve readability.

The compiler completely ignores these separators.

Syntax

1'000'000

0b1010'1100

0xFF'EE

-----------------------------------------

2. Why were Digit Separators introduced?

Large numbers are difficult to read.

Example

1000000000

Is this

100 million?

or

1 billion?

Instead write

1'000'000'000

which is much easier to read.

-----------------------------------------

3. Example

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int x = 1'000'000;

    cout << x;

    return 0;
}

Output

1000000

The compiler ignores the quotes.

-----------------------------------------

4. Binary Example

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int x = 0b1010'1111;

    cout << x;

    return 0;
}

Output

175

The separator only improves readability.

-----------------------------------------

5. Hexadecimal Example

int x = 0xFF'AA;

Same as

0xFFAA

-----------------------------------------

6. Floating Point Example

double pi = 3.141'592'653;

double salary = 10'000.50;

Both are valid.

-----------------------------------------

7. Long Integer Example

long long population = 1'450'000'000LL;

Much easier to read than

1450000000LL

-----------------------------------------

8. Where can Digit Separators be used?

✔ Decimal literals

1'000'000

✔ Binary literals

0b1111'0000

✔ Hexadecimal literals

0xAB'CD

✔ Floating point numbers

123'456.789

✔ Long long literals

1'000'000LL

-----------------------------------------

9. Where CANNOT they be used?

Not at the beginning

'1000

Invalid

Not at the end

1000'

Invalid

Cannot be consecutive

1''000

Invalid

Cannot replace decimal point

3'14

Invalid

Correct

3.14

-----------------------------------------

10. Does it affect memory?

No.

Example

int a = 1000000;

int b = 1'000'000;

Both occupy exactly the same memory.

Both have the same value.

The separator is ignored by the compiler.

-----------------------------------------

11. Why use Digit Separators?

Improves readability.

Makes large constants easier to understand.

Especially useful in

• Financial software
• Scientific calculations
• Bit masks
• Embedded programming
• Networking
• Configuration values

-----------------------------------------

12. Examples

Decimal

1'000'000

Binary

0b1010'1100

Hexadecimal

0xAB'CD

Floating Point

123'456.789

Long Long

1'000'000LL

-----------------------------------------

13. Advantages

• Improves readability

• Reduces mistakes

• Makes binary and hexadecimal values easier to understand

• No runtime overhead

• No extra memory usage

